{"id":"1504.03603","submitter":"Nicolas Brunner","authors":"Ralph Silva, Paul Skrzypczyk, Nicolas Brunner","title":"A small quantum absorption refrigerator with reversed couplings","comments":"7 pages, 3 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. E 92, 012136 (2015)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevE.92.012136","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Small quantum absorption refrigerators have recently attracted renewed\nattention. Here we present a missing design of a two-qubit fridge, the main\nfeature of which is that one of the two machine qubits is itself maintained at\na temperature colder than the cold bath. This is achieved by 'reversing' the\ncouplings to the baths compared to previous designs, where only a transition is\nmaintained cold. We characterize the working regime and the efficiency of the\nfridge. We demonstrate the soundness of the model by deriving and solving a\nmaster equation. Finally, we discuss the performance of the fridge, in\nparticular the heat current extracted from the cold bath. We show that our\nmodel performs comparably to the standard three-level quantum fridge, and thus\nappears appealing for possible implementations of nano thermal machines.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 14 Apr 2015 16:10:29 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-08-04"}
